---
import Footer from "../components/layout/footer.astro";
import Layout from "../components/layout/layout.astro";

const stack = [
  ["Engine", "Phaser 4 — 2.5D look on a 2D field"],
  ["Netcode", "Peer-to-peer WebRTC, host-authoritative"],
  ["Sound", "Chiptune SFX synthesized in Web Audio"],
  ["Platform", "Astro on Wix Headless hosting"],
  ["Accounts", "Wix Members — optional, for avatars & progress"],
];
---

<Layout
  title="About — TeamBuild Games"
  description="Why we built a tiny arcade for teambuildings, and what's under the hood."
>
  <div class="mx-auto w-full max-w-3xl px-4 py-16">
    <p class="eyebrow text-cyan-400">Player's manual</p>
    <h1 class="mt-3 font-display text-2xl text-white sm:text-3xl">
      About the arcade
    </h1>

    <div class="mt-10 space-y-10 text-neutral-300">
      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-xs text-cyan-300">What this is</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed">
          TeamBuild Games is a small pack of multiplayer browser games built
          for one job: giving your team something to actually
          <em>play</em> together. No downloads, no accounts, no procurement
          form — one person opens a room, shares a link, and everyone's in.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-xs text-fuchsia-300">Why it exists</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed">
          Most teambuilding is a slideshow with extra steps. Fifteen minutes of
          dashing, aiming, and yelling at each other in an arena does more for
          a team than an hour of structured icebreakers — especially for
          remote and hybrid teams who never share a room. Games are short by
          design: quick rounds, instant rematches, and just enough chaos to
          generate stories for the next coffee break.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-xs text-emerald-300">Under the hood</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed">
          For the technically curious: matches run peer-to-peer over WebRTC —
          one player's browser hosts the simulation, everyone else streams
          inputs to it. Every game runs on a deterministic core, so if the
          host rage-quits, another player takes over mid-match without missing
          a tick.
        </p>
        <dl class="mt-6 divide-y divide-white/10 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-night-900">
          {
            stack.map(([label, value]) => (
              <div class="flex flex-col gap-1 px-5 py-3 sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
                <dt class="font-display text-[9px] text-neutral-500">{label}</dt>
                <dd class="text-sm text-neutral-300">{value}</dd>
              </div>
            ))
          }
        </dl>
      </section>

      <section class="pixel-grid rounded-2xl border border-cyan-400/30 bg-night-900 px-6 py-10 text-center">
        <p class="font-display text-xs leading-relaxed text-white">
          Enough reading.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-6 flex justify-center">
          <a href="/games/arena" class="arcade-btn">▶ Play Arena</a>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>
  <Footer />
</Layout>
